Problem 1

Create a data frame

  1. The chunk below creates a data frame comprised of:
  • a random sample of size 8 from a standard Normal distribution
  • a logical vector indicating whether elements of the sample are greater than 0
  • a character vector of length 8
  • a factor vector of length 8, with 3 different factor levels
df1 = tibble(
  vec_numeric = rnorm(8),
  vec_logical = vec_numeric > 0,
  vec_char = c("s", "o", "m", "e", "c", "h", "a", "r"),
  vec_factor = factor(c("butterfly", "dream", "Zhuang", "dream", "butterfly", "dream", "Zhuang", "dream"))
)
  1. Try to take the mean of each variable in the dataframe
  • The mean of the numeric vector is -0.148822.
  • The mean of the logical vector is 0.5.
  • The mean of the character vector is NA.
  • The mean of the factor vector is NA.

As illustrated above, taking the mean of the numeric and logical vectors works, but taking the mean of the character and factor vectors does not work. Taking the mean of logical vector works because R is assigning numeric values to the logical vector (1 to all true values and 0 to all flase ones). Therefore taking the mean of logical vectors works as well.

  1. Write a code chunk that applies the as.numeric function to the logical, character, and factor variables
  • convert the logical vector to numeric, and multiply the random sample by the result
  • convert the logical vector to a factor, and multiply the random sample by the result
  • convert the logical vector to a factor and then convert the result to numeric, and multiply the random sample by the result
log2num = as.numeric(pull(df1, vec_logical)) * pull(df1, vec_numeric)
log2fac = as.factor(pull(df1, vec_logical)) * pull(df1, vec_numeric)
log2fac2num = as.numeric(as.factor(pull(df1, vec_logical))) * pull(df1, vec_numeric)

From the results, log2fac returns a vector of 8 NAs, and it shows the warning that * not meaningful for factors, because factor vectors cannot be converted to numeirc values. This also explains why it failed to take the mean of factor vectors. Since factor vectors do not have numeric values, it is not meaningful to take the mean of them, and therefore we got NAs and warning messages.

Problem 2

  1. Create a data frame comprised of:
  • x: a random sample of size 500 from a standard Normal distribution
  • y: a random sample of size 500 from a standard Normal distribution
  • A logical vector indicating whether x + y > 1
  • A numeric vector created by coercing the above logical vector
  • A factor vector created by coercing the above logical vector
df2 = tibble(
  x = rnorm(500),
  y = rnorm(500),
  vec_log = x + y > 1,
  vec_num = as.numeric(vec_log),
  vec_fac = as.factor(vec_log)
)

This dataset has 500 rows and 5 columns. The mean of x in the dataset is 0.0351631, the median of x is 0.1126382, and the standard deviation is 1.0346842. In 136 of the 500 cases, x + y > 1.

scatter_log = ggplot(df2, aes(x = x, y = y, color = vec_log)) + geom_point() + labs(title = "scatterplot by logical variable", x = "x", y = "y")
ggsave("scatter_log.png")
## Saving 7 x 5 in image
scatter_log

scatter_num = ggplot(df2, aes(x = x, y = y, color = vec_num)) + geom_point() + labs(title = "scatterplot by numerical variable", x = "x", y = "y")
scatter_num

scatter_fac = ggplot(df2, aes(x = x, y = y, color = vec_fac)) + geom_point() + labs(title = "scatterplot by factor variable", x = "x", y = "y")
scatter_fac

As depicted in the first scatterplot (scatter_log), the TRUE ones (x + y > 1) are in green and FALSE ones (x + y < 1) are in red. The color of each point is determined by the logical vector of the data set df2. As depicted in the second scatterplot (scatter_num), data points with a value of 1 (x + y > 1) are in green and data points with a value of 0 (x + y < 1) are in red. In fact, the color distribution is similar to the first scatterplot, as the color of each point is determined by the numerical vector of the data set df2, and the numerical vector is created by coercing the logical vector. As depicted in the third scatterplot (scatter_fac), similar to the first scatterplot, the TRUE ones (x + y > 1) are in green and FALSE ones (x + y < 1) are in red. The color of each point is determined by the factor vector of the data set df2. The color distribution is similar to the first scatterplot, as the color of each point is determined by the factor vector of the data set df2, and the factor vector is created by coercing the logical vector.
